Explanation of the execution of an adduct relation rule. Below is presented an example of adduct relation rule explanation in JSON (assuming a [particular context](https://raw.githubusercontent.com/marianofl1971/lis/master/OnToology/lis.owl/context/context.jsonld)): ~~~~ { "coreInformation":"The empirical compound 517.3172@19.4689 is expected to be the theoretical compound PC(O-14:0/2:0) with adduct M+Na, because, for example, the empirical compound 495.3352@19.4689 with adduct M+H may be the theoretical compound PC(O-14:0/2:0) as well." }
~~~~ and here, an example in JSON-LD: ~~~~ { "@context": "https://raw.githubusercontent.com/marianofl1971/lis/master/OnToology/lis.owl/context/context.jsonld", "@type":"https://w3id.org/def/lis#ARRExplanation",
"coreInformation":"The empirical compound 517.3172@19.4689 is expected to be the theoretical compound PC(O-14:0/2:0) with adduct M+Na, because, for example, the empirical compound 495.3352@19.4689 with adduct M+H may be the theoretical compound PC(O-14:0/2:0) as well." } ~~~~

An experiment has an identifier, a ionisation mode, (optionally) a modifier, and a collection of hypotheses. Below is presented an example of experiment in JSON (assuming a [particular context](https://raw.githubusercontent.com/marianofl1971/lis/master/OnToology/lis.owl/context/context.jsonld)). Although this example includes it, the modifier can be omitted. In such a case, it is assumed that there is no modifier:
