LIS takes as input an experiment.

A hypothesis is characterised by an empirical compound, a theoretical compound and an adduct. Below is presented an example of hypothesis in JSON (assuming a [particular context](https://raw.githubusercontent.com/marianofl1971/lis/master/OnToology/lis.owl/context/context.jsonld)):
~~~~
{
    "identifier": 3,
    "empiricalCompound": {
       "mass": 399.3367,
       "retentionTime": 18.8425
     },
     "theoreticalCompound": {
        "identifier": 32675,
        "name": "L-palmitoylcarnitine"
     },
     "adduct": "M+H"
}
~~~~
and here, an example in JSON-LD:
~~~~
{
    "@context": "https://raw.githubusercontent.com/marianofl1971/lis/master/OnToology/lis.owl/context/context.jsonld",
    "@type": "https://w3id.org/def/lis#Hypothesis",

    "identifier": 3,
    "empiricalCompound": {
       "mass": 399.3367,
       "retentionTime": 18.8425
     },
     "theoreticalCompound": {
        "identifier": 32675,
        "name": "L-palmitoylcarnitine"
     },
     "adduct": "M+H"
}
~~~~

It is a substance that plays the role of modifier in an experiment. The possible modifieres are

- NH3;
- HCOO;
- CH3COO;
- HCOONH3; or
- CH3COONH3
